uk.gov.gchq.koryphe.adapted

Class Adapted<I,AI,AO,O,C>

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.gov.gchq.koryphe.adapted.InputAdapted<I,AI>
      • uk.gov.gchq.koryphe.adapted.Adapted<I,AI,AO,O,C>
  • Type Parameters:
    I - Input type
    AI - Type adapted from input
    AO - Type to be adapted to output
    O - Output type
    C - Context type - either I or O, depending on context.
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AdaptedBinaryOperator, AdaptedFunction

    public abstract class Adapted<I,AI,AO,O,C>
extends InputAdapted<I,AI>
    An Adapted class is one that applies functions to it's inputs and outputs, allowing it to be applied to different input and output types. It can also be used to apply a function to values contained within a complex object. For example, if we wanted to apply the existing function (i -> i+1) to increment a specific integer member variable count of a context object (co), we could use an Adapted function with the input adapter function (co -> co.getCount()) and the output adapter function ((co, o) -> co.setCount(o)). The context type C is the type supplied to the output adapter to combine with the type AO to produce the output type O. An Adapted Function might merge it's output into the input type, as in the example above, while an Adapted BiFunction would merge it's output into some state object.
